The paper deals with a visual localization system for multi-vehicle long-term operations in outdoor environments, which involves robotics (cs.RO) and computer vision (cs.CV) techniques. The paper also discusses the challenges of processing large amounts of data subject to limited computational and storage capabilities, which could fall under machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper proposes a map management process that allows building and maintaining maps for precise visual localization, which could be relevant to systems and control (cs.SY).
